"ogimage":"http://s3-media1.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/qblKfvjtcjpaKc_oliAlEw/l.jpg",
"rating":"4.5",
"reviewcomment":"Love at first sight- the 12th sight and every single time after!! <br><br>I first saw this monumental landmark  back in 2009.My first trip to Roma and first trip to Colosseo. It was every bit as mind blowing as you&#39;ve pictured and then some. To think this landmark is still standing after almost 2,000 years- how can you not be blown away by it? <br><br>Needless to say I fell in love with this stunning beauty.  I&#39;ve been going back every summer since 2009!!  :)<br><br>Tips<br>My first trip- I went inside with a guided tour. If you are with a tour group, large or small, you skip the lines. Instead of 3 hours, you will spend about an hour. It was overwhelming and hot! ( Roman summers are hot and humid) <br><br>My second trip 2011- I skipped all the tour guides on this trip and had a much more relax and fun time. We walked to Colosseo during the day time for a peak of that beauty. And at night time. No matter how stunning Colosseo maybe during the day time, night time view is the one you want. So majestic with lights all around. It is simply magical. <br><br>After several more trips (last one in 2013)- I&#39;ve discovered a perfect time for daily Colosseo visits. Right before sunset. Colosseo closes at 5 pm. If you come right at 5 pm for a 6 pm sunset: you are set. You will avoid the tour groups/crowds and lines. If you want a perfect sunset pictures inside, come right around 4:30. You can avoid big lines and get right in. They won&#39;t kick you out till 6-6:30 pm. And you can get perfect sunset pictures with stunning lights. <br><br>If you come here after sundown - 9 pm: you will not see any tourists at all. Of course you won&#39;t be able to get inside but you can hang outside. Sit around the benches. You&#39;ll see a lot of Romans (couples, singles) just hanging out as Colosseo stand tall in the background. If you do come in September, bring a light jacket. It gets a little bit cold at night. The walk from via del coros to here will take you about a good 20-25 minutes one way. Overall- a night stroll should take you a good hour or two. And it is time well spent. You can stop at Vittorio Emanuele II and watch those soldiers. Take a long stroll beside the Forums. And get extremely excited as you walk straight down to this beautiful landmark. Doesn&#39;t matter how many times you&#39;ve seen it, it will still take your breath away. I&#39;ve seen it over 3 dozen times in 5 different summers...yet I can&#39;t wait to see it again!!  Absolute must see in Rome- both during the day and at night! Love love love.",
