"ogimage":"http://s3-media1.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/p9noPa4zmooAJtbsBKd8Lw/l.jpg",
"rating":"4.0",
"reviewcomment":"So first, being American, it&#39;s not common for me to sit at long tables with total strangers. I thought it would be weird, and in fact it was a bit weird at first, but you get used to it. While we didn&#39;t converse with the people next to us, they were nice enough and said hello and then just went about their conversations.<br><br>And second, being American, my expectations of service are a little different than what you end up getting in Europe. At busy times, they seat you and don&#39;t really bother with you unless you flag them over ... so I guess that&#39;s a cultural thing that I just need to get used to. Regardless, our waitress was efficient enough that it didn&#39;t bother me. She was pleasant and gave suggestions for buying a glass of wine (even though it&#39;s not in the menu anywhere). She also brought out the accoutrements with our food (i.e., the salt and pepper, the cheese, etc.) without being asked.<br><br>The food was quite good. The bread was tasty, though be warned they charge you for it if you eat it. I&#39;d recommend the cacio e pepe; a simple dish of pasta, butter, cheese and pepper, which is definitely greater than the sum of it&#39;s parts. It was simple, elegant and very flavorful. The gnocchi was also quite good; you could tell the sauce was fresh and it had nice flavor. They also brought <br><br>Taking cue from other European eaters, we stretched the meal out to 1.5 hours and had a couple nice glasses of wine and enjoyed the hustle and bustle of a popular tourist street.<br><br>Another plus was that it&#39;s very close to Trevi fountain, so you can make it an extra romantic evening with your sweetie by finishing up dinner and grabbing some gelato to savor at the fountain (with a thousand other people doing the same thing).",
